column168: Phillips 66 loaded the four tank cars (GATX 231130, TILX 101963, TILX 101981, and TILX 101944) at its Wood River refinery with spent sulfuric acid and released them at approximately 7:11 am CT on 5/25/21.  NS then pulled the cars from the refinery and placed them at the Wilds Yard in Wood River.  At the time NS pulled the cars from Phillips 66 and placed them in the Wilds Yard they were not venting.  All four cars were spotted to the industry switch track and interchanged for pickup by Kansas City Southern Railroad (?KCS?) at 7:00 am CT on 5/27/21.  KCS did not arrive for pickup of the cars until 6/2/21. KCS hooked up to the cars in the afternoon of 6/2/21 and, in the process of releasing the brake system, discovered that GATX 231130 was venting.  KCS unhooked, pulled away, and the conductor requested medical assistance and was taken to a local hospital, but was not admitted.  The other three cars (TILX 101963, TILX101981 and TILX 101944) began venting on 6/3/21.  NS mobilized its hazardous materials incident response team to assist the Wood River Fire Department with emergency response on 6/2/21. Phillips 66?s fire department, Madison County Emergency Management/Madison County Hazmat, and the Wood River Police also responded. Remedial measures including water curtains and air scrubbing units were used to mitigate the release from 6/3/21 to 6/7/21.  On 6/7/21 and 6/8/21 responders replaced/repaired components of the pressure relief devices (?PRDs?) on the tank cars.  At 7:00 pm CT on 6/8/21 all four tank cars were moved back into the Phillips 66 refinery.  The tank cars began venting due to Phillips 66?s spent sulfuric acid undergoing a polymeric reaction, which created overpressurization that released through the PRDs on the four tank cars.

column25: YFA Group, Elisa, G/F Block A&B, Wah Tat Industrial Centre
column168: Mott Corp. purchased Titanium powder from a supplier in China by the name of Chengdu Huarui Industrial Co., Ltd. Before sending to us, our Powder Engineer asked them to ensure the material was sent in accordance with all dangerous goods regulations. Huarui sent him a photo of what the (2) packages filled with powder looked like before sending. Both packages had a flammable label on them as well as a "cargo aircraft only" sticker. The box had a UN symbol on it and numbers next to it that were blurred out in the photo. Shipping labels were not able to be seen in the photo. When the packages arrived at Mott on July 1, DHL did not have the shipping papers for the material so it stayed in Shipping until they were able to receive it in. I (Crystal Steinfeld, EHS Manager for Mott) discovered on July 7 that the powder had been delivered and asked to see the packages. The flammable label and "cargo aircraft only" stickers were not on the packages and the UN symbol and numbers were covered up with tape. The only form of identification of the Titanium powder was found on the DHL label in extremely small writing: "Contents - Titanium Hydride Powder". One of the packages weighed 30 lbs in total (powder by itself 28.08lbs) and the second package weighed 28.68 lbs (powder by itself 26.72lbs). Each package contained three bags with smaller vacuum sealed bags of powder in each of those bags. There are a total of 8 vacuum sealed bags of powder. The packages are currently being quarantined.
column169: There needs to be very clear communication between the carriers who have been hired to ship the hazardous material and the origin country (Hong Kong, China) in this case. We really need to understand China's laws for shipping hazardous materials because from what I am learning throughout this process, China does not allow hazardous material to leave their country. There is a disconnect from the material leaving the supplier facility and leaving Hong Kong via aircraft. The carriers need to closely follow and trace all materials they are signing up to ship out of China and specifically that airport because it seems as though someone covered up the hazardous information in order to get it out of China. Items need to be checked thoroughly before getting on an aircraft to avoid someone getting seriously harmed.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: On 07/03/2021 at about 8:30 AM, a Veolia employee entered the back of a box van to move a 55 gallon drum from the truck to a trailer at the Veolia, Schenectady, NY facility.  The container was not leaking when the employee prepared to move it. Immediately after lifting the 55 gallon with a drum cart, the bottom of the container started to leak. There were four holes in the container on two opposing sides of the bottom of the drum. The holes were two by two and similar to a vampire bite. The Veolia employee investigated the source of the leak but could not figure out what caused the holes. We looked at the possibility of a defective drum cart but could not find anything. The drum was fairly old and rusty and the holes could have developed due to the age of the drum and/or the material within the drum causing deterioration, or the drum could have been defective.  About 1 liter of a waste flammable liquid leaked into the box van. No liquid made it outside of the box van. The drum was overpacked and the liquid on the truck floor was cleaned up.
column169: There are several follow up items that were reviewed to try and prevent a recurrence. At first thought, we thought a drum cart may have caused the holes on the bottom of the container but we inspected the drum carts and did not find any defects that could have caused the holes. We also reviewed the contents of the drum and it is possible that material may have been put in the drum that corroded it from the inside and caused the leak. Also the drum could have been defective at the time of purchase. The drum did not start to leak until we moved it after a three hour trip. Veolia employees will continue to do inspections of containers, tools, and surfaces at time of shipment and at time of transfer to try and prevent similar leaks from happening.

column25: City of Fort Worth Environmental Collection Center
column168: On July 12, 2021 a Veolia employee arrived at the office at 6:30 am and began the daily facility walk around inspection after the weekend. Upon entering the warehouse the employee could smell a strong Chlorine smell and as he was waiting for the lights to come on he noticed something sitting in the middle of the warehouse floor. As the light got brighter he could see that it was a drum lid. The Veolia employee located the drum that the lid had come from.  It appears that it had pressurized over the weekend and blew the lid off. There was no physical damage to the building or any other drum.  Veolia is letting drum gas off more before putting on a new lid that is equipped with a vent to prevent it from building anymore pressure.    NOTE: The electronic 5800.1 form would not accept "no release" as a consequence of the incident.  There were no leaks from the drum and no hazardous materials spilled as a result of the incident.
column169: In the future, all containers loaded with this material will be equipped with a vent to manage any pressure build up that may occur within the drum.

column168: The shipment TCLU 8090950  B/L  60729681 was offered under a vessel sharing agreement to Hapag-Lloyd, for transport on the Hapag-Lloyd container vessel Bremen Express from SAVANNAH, GA to GENOA, ITALY.  Shipper (SCHENKER) advised Hapag-Lloyd after the vessel had sailed from SAVANNAH, GA  of the following hazardous material in the container that was not original booked or otherwise identified.  - UN3077, ENVIRONMENTALLY HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE SOLID, N.O.S. (Zinc Oxide), Class 9), PG III, MP  The shipping papers that accompanied the freight container to the marine terminal did not indicate the presence of the additional hazardous material, and the container was not placarded and/or marked to reflect the presence of the additional items.  Shipper subsequently provided corrected hazardous material shipping papers to Hapag-Lloyd

A LOADER ON THE RED BELT DOOR 265 NOTICED A STRONG ODOR COMING FROM THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS PACKAGE. UPON INSPECTION IN THE DMP A RESPONDER FOUND THAT ALL 4 BOTTLES OF ETHYL ETHER WERE LEAKING FROM THEIR CLOSURE. THE ODOR WAS SO INTENSE THAT THE RESPONDER DONNED THE SCBA FOR THE REMAINDER OF INSPECTION AND PROCESSING. THE ETHER HAD LEAKED THROUGH THE PACKAGE AND EATEN AWAY AT THE ENCLOSED PACKING MATERIAL LEAVING THE RESIDUE WITHIN AND STUCK ON THE INSIDE OF THE BOX. ALL 4 BOTTLE CAPS WERE ABLE TO BE TURNED BETWEEN A HALF OF TURN AND 1 AND HALF TURNS BEFORE BEING FULLY CLOSED. ALL 4 BOTTLES HAD DAMAGE TO THEIR LABELS AND MISSING CONTENTS SO THEY WERE ALL PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP.

FULLY LABELED HAZ-MAT SHIPMENT WAS VISUALLY DISCOVERED WET IN APPEARANCE AND EMITTING A PUNGENT ODOR BY A LOADER ON THE SD-1/2. WITHOUT TOUCHING THE PKG HE EVACUATED THE AREA AND NOTIFIED HIS IMMEDIATE SUPERVISOR. DMP WAS CONTACTED AND WITHIN 2 MINUTES A RESPONDER ARRIVED, DONNING THE PROPER PPE. AFTER FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE   APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET THE DAMAGE WAS CONTAINED (NO SPILLAGE OUTSIDE OF CARTON), THEN TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA. CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE CAPS ON 6 OF 6 PLASTIC 1-GAL JUGS WERE LOOSE BY 1/4 ROTATION, WHICH CAUSED A COUPLE OUNCES FROM EACH ONE TO LEAK OUT OF THE BREACH(S) AND INTO THE BOTTOM SECTION OF THE CARTON. THE INNER PACKING MATERIAL CONSISTED OF A 6 CONFIGURATION CORRUGATED DIVIDER, AND THE OUTER CARTON WAS A DOUBLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX, RATED AT A 350 LBS PER SQ INCH BURSTING TEST.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: Driver was having trailer inspected at a Speed Co. shop associated with a Loved Truck Stop in Greenwood, LA. The truck and trailer were inside the shop bay. The technician conducting the inspection advised that the trailer was leaking. The material leaked onto a concrete floor. A hazmat response was summoned and 3E Environmental responded and mitigated the leaking tote. The contents was transferred to another tote and the released material was absorbed with absorbent material. The remediated waste was packed in a salvage drum and removed by 3E Environmental.
column169: The tote was inspected by the driver upon accepting the load that originated at Clean Harbors Deer Park LLC in LaPorte TX. The load was periodically checked during transportation from LaPorte, TX to Greenwood, LA. with no signs of the tote being compromised. The tote was on a pallet and it was determined that a nail from the pallet had punctured the bottom of the tote during transportation. It would be best if IBC totes were not on pallets, thereby eliminating the possibility of a nail puncturing the poly tote during transportation.

column168: This release of Sulfuric Acid was caused by lack of load securement. The drum tipped over on its side on the van trailer it was being transported in. The release was due to the head and retention ring system allowing material to be release from the drum while it was laid on its side. Due to the minimal amount of material released, the drum must have tipped over shortly before the release was noticed. The drum was righted, the released material was remediated with absorbent mats and both the drum and the remediation waste was over-packed in a salvage drum.
column169: The facility will conduct remedial training with the driver regarding proper load securement and the driver will demonstrate for management the proper way to secure the drum by means of load securement straps to the load retention system present in our van trailers.

HYDROCHLORIC ACID SPILL TODAY IN DOOR 14.ON WEDNESDAY, JULY 14 AT APPROXIMATELY 11:45 A.M. RESPONDED TO A CALL IN DOOR 14 IN THE ALDERWOOD CONTAINERIZED THE SPILL AND STARTING BRINGING THE CONTENTS BACK TO THE CAGE. ONE OF THE CAPS WAS OFF, SO I DID A PH TEST AND FOUND THE PRODUCT TO BE A 0-1 ON THE INDICATOR BAR. PULLED UP THE SDS FOR THE PRODUCT A PRODUCT WITH UP TO 16% CONCENTRATION OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID. I ALSO NOTICED PER SECTION 14 OF THE SDS THAT THE PRODUCT WAS A CORROSIVE. THERE WERE NO EXTERNAL MARKINGS OR PAPER WORK TO INDICATED THAT A HAZMAT WAS INSIDE. I IMMEDIATELY WENT TO THE SUPERVISOR TO LET HIM KNOW OF THE SEVERITY OF THE PRODUCT.I PRINTED SDS.THERE WERE APPROXIMATELY SIX LARGE AFFECTED PACKAGES THAT ABSORBED THE MAJORITY OF THE PRODUCT INCLUDING A FOLDED UP MATTRESS.

column168: On 07/24/2021 at 1259 hours EST CSXT personnel in the Florence Yard discovered GATX53691, a  loaded tank car of Acetonitrile, Toluene leaking from top of the car. The car was isolated and the  shipper, Clean Harbors was notified. Marion Environmental Inc (MEI), a CSXT response contractor,  responded and found product on the side of the tank car and two manway bolts applied hand tight.  The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Clean Harbors (Matt Hurley 800-645-8265). MEI put a manway gasket on the tank car which it did not have, and  applied all manway bolts and tightened the bolts tool tight.  The car was released back into transportation.
column169: (NAR code: 200 5  What Failed: Manway, Hinged & Bolted  Where Failed: Connection between manway nozzle and manway cover  Why Failed: Bolts/nuts - less than tool tight )

column168: On July 16, 2021, at approximately 12:30 pm CDT, a tractor-trailer operated by R+L Carriers (R+L) was making a delivery at the above-referenced customer location when one (1) 55-gallon drum of Super Sperse (containing diethanolamine) was discovered with a loose cap. As a result, approximately one (1) gallon of product released to the trailer floor during transit. RLC retained Cura Emergency Services, LC (CES), who dispatched a crew First Call Environmental, LLC (FCE) to perform the necessary corrective action. FCE resecured the closure cap and utilized absorbents to remediate the release.

column42: AMMONIUM NITRATE EMULSION OR AMMONIUM NITRATE SUSPENSION OR AMMONIUM NITRATE GEL, INTERMEDIATE FOR BLASTING EXPLOSIVES
column168: On Friday July 2, 2021 at about 16:00, an Austin Powder Company driver was making a delivery of ammonium nitrate emulsion (UN3375) into a bin at the Austin location in Newnan, GA.  This involves pumping the product from the package (DOT 407 spec tank) into the bin.  Austin policy states that the driver attend the process in case of a malfunction and/or release of product.  The driver did not follow this procedure, and was away from the truck in an unknown location.  Driver reported that he was operating the PTO at normal rate.  However, the onsite manager and safety personnel suspect that the PTO was operating at higher than prescribed RPMs (to speed the process).  This is based on the fact that this driver had a similar incident a short time ago.  The driver called into his dispatcher, reporting a "dinner plate sized" amount of spilled material.  It was later found that the release was actually much larger than was initially reported.  A local cleanup crew was called and arrived at the scene on Monday morning, and they worked throughout the day, cleaning up the spilled product as well as impacted muddy soil.  All told, an estimated 2500-3000 lbs of material was cleaned up, removed from the site, and taken away for profiling and ultimate disposal.
column169: The driver, who had a history of this type of event, was terminated.  The other drivers who make similar deliveries of this type of product (roughly 30 drivers) were all counseled in the wake of this event.  Specifically, remaining in attendance of vehicles offloading product, and operating PTO at normal RPMs was covered with them.  It is my belief that this event has brought the issue to adequate attention of the other drivers to prevent similar events in the future.  We have also looked at our rupture disks (currently getting from 2 different suppliers).  We do not see any correlation between which disks were in use when the events have occurred.  Finally, our engineers are working with an outside company to potentially develop a system that would feed the outlet hose back into the tank by placing the product into a reservoir, rather than directly onto the ground in a situation where a disk bursts.

THE INNER PACKING MATERIAL CONSISTED OF INDIVIDUAL NON-CORRUGATED CARTONS SURROUNDING EACH CONTAINER AND THE OUTER CARTON WAS A SINGLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX, RATED AT A 200 LBS PER SQ INCH BURSTING TEST.

column168: The Veolia field services team was loading a pallet of 4 drums (which had been visually inspected for proper closure) onto truck at the customer's site when the pallet abruptly stopped after hitting another pallet. A 551a2 drum of waste paint fell over and started leaking out from around the lid ring. The team immediately got the drum upright and started cleaning the spill with spill pads.    When the Veolia employees attempted to retighten the drum ring but it continued to leak. This led the team to come to the conclusion that the customer used a lid without an o-ring to close the drum. The team opened the drum and verified that indeed there was no gasket in the lid. The customer brought out a new lid for the drum so that the original lid could be replaced. While the drum was open the customer inspected the contents and stated that about 1-2 gallons had escaped the drum. The paint did escape the box and spilled on to the fuel tank of the truck and the ground. Our team was able to place spill pad under the truck to collect most of the material before it hit the ground.    The customer took responsibility to clean material that had made it to the ground with spill dry and removal of contaminated gravel.
column169: Veolia employees counseled the customer on the importance of using the right containers with all the appropriate pieces to ensure this doesn't occur again. The team also provided tips for identifying leaks around the the drum ring.

column168: HAZMAT PACKAGE WAS FOUND IN TRAILER DOOR 3 AND RESPONDER WAS CALLED. AFTER REMOVING BOXES THAT WERE NOT LEAKED ON OR DAMAGED, A PH TEST STRIP WAS USED ON SPILLED LIQUID, WHICH WAS ABOUT 10 OR 11 ON PH SCALE. AFTER USING SODIUM BICARBONATE TO NEUTRALIZE, ANOTHER PH TESTING STRIP WAS USED TO CONFIRM NEUTRALITY. AFTERWARDS, ZEP ZORBENT WAS USED TO SOLIDIFY AND PACKAGES THAT WERE LEAKED ON/DAMAGED BY THE HAZMAT WERE SENT IN SPILL TUBS AND SENT TO DMP. PACKAGES WERE PLACED IN A WELL VENTILATED AREA AND PLACED IN GREEN DMP BAGS AS THE PROCESS OF DISPOSING/CONTAINMENT WAS FOLLOWED THROUGH. NON-HAZMAT PACKAGES THAT COULD BE SALVAGED WERE REPACKAGED AND SENT ON.

column168: On July 21, 2021, at approximately 6:00 a.m. CDT, a tractor-trailer operated by Harcros Chemical, Inc. (HCI) was traveling near the above-referenced location when a load shift occurred. As a result, one (1) 330-gallon tote containing ammonia solutions was punctured and released approximately 330 gallons of product to the trailer floor. Free product further migrated to the asphalt roadway and adjacent soil area. AIG Environmental Specialty Claims Consultants (AIG) retained Cura Emergency Services, LC (CES) to manage the remediation on behalf of HCI. CES dispatched a crew from Hull's Environmental Services (HES) to perform the necessary corrective action. HES removed all cargo from the trailer, deployed absorbents and neutralizing agent to the impacted surfaces, and relocated the damaged tote into a new trailer for transport back to HCI. All spent material was collected and containerized into three (3) 55-gallon drums for transport and disposal. HES then hand-dug a trench around the soil impact area and placed absorbent boom, scheduling to return at a later date for excavation operations to complete remedial actions.

column168: On July 23, 2021 at 1420 hours, CN transportation crews observed liquid splashing from the top of GATX 5604 / UN1832 / Sulfuric Acid, Spent, Class 8 / PG II / Load, at CN Mays Yard, Harahan, La.  The railcar was isolated, and all appropriate notifications were made. CN's response team responded and observed signs of liquid splash coming from the top of the railcar.  Upon closer inspection, the fill hole cover swing bolts were found not properly secured.  The washer on one of the swing bolts was observed between the cover and railcar nozzle not allowing the cover to be fully seated.  The fill hole cover was properly secured with the washers and bolts above the fill hole cover, which secured the leak.  The exterior of the railcar was deconned.  The railcar was released and allowed to continue onto destination.

RLC retained Cura Emergency Services, LC (CES), who dispatched a crew from EnviroServe (ES) to perform the necessary corrective action. column168: RRTS contacted ERTS requested clean up/decontamination of a trailer floor that had a spill of UN 2468 that is located at a customer location Sun Logistics 12250 NW 28th Ave, Miami, FL. 6 - 5gallon poly pails that were damaged and will also need to be disposed of along with the clean up debris from the trailer. The site contact stated the pails are in the terminal and he will provide a location for them once the contractor arrives on site. He stated he believes that approximately 1/2 of the length of the trailer floor was impacted by the release. The contractor reports the trailer floor impacts (area approximately 8-ft by 4-ft) has been cleaned. The contractor advised that the entire floor (53-ft. by 8-ft.) was cleaned-swept since the impacts were dry and light; contractor applied sodium bicarbonate to impacted area; contractor hand brushed sodium bicarbonate into the floor; collected and containerized waste into a 95-gallon overpack poly drum; contractor identified six, 5-gallon poly pails of material that were damaged-crushed; one pail was damaged-cracked that apparently leaked; all containers (6) were containerized in one, 95-gallon over-pack poly drum with the waste from trailer; the one, 95-gallon overpack of solid waste was transported off-site by contractor for pending profiling/disposal;

The leaking pails were re-secured and accepted by the consignee. The contractor departed the site with the waste generated.

column168: PACKAGE CAR DRIVER CAME TO RESPONDER CAGE AND INDICATED THERE WAS A VERY MALODOROUS, UNLABELED PRESUMED HAZMAT PACKAGE THAT WAS BADLY LEAKING ON THE REAR FLOOR OF HIS PACKAGE CAR. UPON ARRIVING AT PACKAGE CAR, WE OPENED THE REAR AND FRONT DOORS TO ALLOW VENTILATION AS THE SCENT WAS EXTREMELY NOXIOUS. ONCE IT HAT AIRED OUT, WE TESTED THE PH, WHICH RATED AS A 1 OR LESS, HIGHLY ACIDIC. AT THAT TIME I TOOK PHOTOS OF THE PACKAGE IN THE VEHICLE. SINCE A STRONG ACID, PER THE DECISION TREE DOCUMENT, I SPREAD A LARGE AMOUNT OF SODIUM BICARBONATE ON THE REMAINS OF THE PACKAGE, THE REMAINS OF THE TOTE IT WAS IN, AND ON THE REAR FLOOR OF THE PACKAGE CAR WHERE IT HAD SPREAD. AT THIS POINT WE PHYSICALLY CLEANED UP THE SPILL AND DEBRIS INTO LINED SPILL CONTAINERS AND RETURNED TO THE RESPONDER CAGE.
FOUND IN THE SOUTH PSC UNDER OTHER PACKAGE. IT WAS IN A SPILL TRAY

DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO PICK UP THIS PACKAGE, BUT IT HAD A DIAMOND LABEL SO THE PICK UP WAS REFUSED.  LATER IN THE DAY THE CUSTOMER BROUGHT THE PACKAGE TO THE CUSTOMER COUNTER DROP OFF LOCATION AND LEFT. THIS TIME THE BOX DID NOT HAVE A DIAMOND LABEL ON IT. CLERK RECOGNIZED THE PACKAGE FROM EARLIER PICK UP REFUSAL.  OPENED BOX TO FIND 5 ENVELOPES EACH WITH 1 BOTTLE OF TRICHLOROETHYLENE, 6.1.  THERE ARE NO DANGEROUS GOODS MARKS OR LABELS ON THE OUTER BOX. THIS PACKAGE HAS NOT BEEN ACCEPTED FOR AIR OR TRANSPORTED IN THE AIR BY UNITED PARCEL SERVICE CO.

column168: FULLY LABELED HAZ-MAT SHIPMENT WAS VISUALLY DISCOVERED LEAKING AND EMITTING A STRONG PUNGENT ODOR IN A TOP CAGE ON BOXLINE-3 BY A SORTER. WITHOUT TOUCHING THE PKG HE TURNED OFF THE POWER TO HALT THE PROGRESS OF THE CAGES, EVACUATED THE AREA AND NOTIFIED HIS IMMEDIATE SUPERVISOR. DMP WAS CONTACTED AND WITHIN A FEW MINUTES A RESPONDER ARRIVED, DONNING THE PROPER PPE. AFTER FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE   APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET, THE DAMAGE WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP (APPROX. 12" RADIUS X 2" DEEP PUDDLE), THEN TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA. CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THERE WAS A MINISCULE PUNCTURE HOLE ON THE BOTTOM OF 1 OF 2 PLASTIC 5 LITER JUGS, CAUSING 1 LITER OF THE LIQUID TO SPILL THROUGH THE BREACH, SATURATING THE BOTTOM AND SPREADING OUTSIDE OF THE CARTON. IT APPEARED THAT THE LEAKING CONTAINER CAME IN CONTACT WITH A SHARP, PROTRUDING OBJECT. THERE WAS NO INTERNAL PACKING MATERIAL AND THE OUTER CARTON WAS A SINGLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX, RATED AT A 44 LBS/IN EDGE CRUSH TEST (ECT).

column168: On 7-30-21 at 1700 personnel in the CSXT Gentilly Yard discovered NATX72699, a loaded tank car  of Sodium Hydrosulforide leaking from top of the car.  The car was isolated and TDC, LLC, were  notified (CHEMTREC Report #2021073000362). SPSI , a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched  to the scene and found the vapors were being released from the vacuum relief device. The issue  identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Veretta Polk and 225-776-0063.  Contractor personnel removed the vacuum relief device and installed a threaded plug to prevent  vapors from being released from the car. The leak was secured and the car is being held to repair  of the vacuum relief device. This incident did not require a special switching move.

While loading freight into a trailer the forklift operator hit a box of hydrochloric acid that was already staged in the trailer with the freight they were loading consequently crushing the box and two of the inner gallon containers. This contributed to an unintentional release and when the spilled material made contacted with the wooden trailer floor it started to smoke prompting the fire alarm to go off dispatching the local fire department to the scene. The facility was evacuated and once on the scene the FD stabilized, neutralized and contained the box and spilled material. The spilled material and damaged container was placed into a recovery container.
column169: Individual boxes of hazardous materials should not be placed into the trailer unprotected and vulnerable to being hit by other freight. This event was reviewed and shared with material handlers and forklift operators to help prevent future occurrences from occurring.

Veolia employees were unloading drums from the box truck to the 10 day trailer in Poca, WV. When the employee picked up the container it began to fume from the ring. The container fumed for roughly 10-20 minutes before it stopped. Trained Veolia employees were able to respond to the event in level B protective gear in order to overpack the container in a poly 95 gallon drum. Further investigation indicated that the material was a corrosive air reactive material that was placed in a steel drum for shipment. This material should have been packed into a poly container. It was also identified that the drum did not have a gasket which allowed material to come in contact with the air causing the material to fume. Once the container was overpacked Veolia did not have any further issues with the container. Veolia employees tightened the remaining 3 drums and safely shipped them with no further issues.
column169: Veolia counseled the customer on the importance of using the proper containers with all the appropriate pieces to ensure this does not occur again. Veolia also provided tips for identifying leaks around the the drum ring.

IT LIST THE CLASSIFICATION AS UN 1760, CORROSIVE LIQUID N.O.S (HYDROCHLORIC ACID AND PHOSPHORIC ACID), CLASS 8, PACKAGING GROUP II. APPROXIMATELY 4 L OF THE MATERIAL SPILLED. SINCE THIS WAS A POSTAL SHIPMENT, I CONFIRMED WITH POSTAL EMPLOYEE RICK EPPERSON THAT USPS WOULD BE DOING REGULATORY NOTIFICATION. I SENT THIS DOT 5800 AS A COURTESY SINCE IT WAS IN OUR POSSESION AS WELL. SOME LIMITED PHOTOS WERE ALSO SENT TO FAA.

column168: Driver of a pickup truck headed southbound on the Sterling Highway (2 lane)  fell asleep at the wheel.  She drove directly into our Northbound lane. Our driver attempted to avoid a head on collision, got around the driver and she made contact with our first tanker near the tail of the tanker.  The set of tankers went over on its side.  The first tanker took the brunt of the damage. only the first tanker released product (crude oil) the tanker was transporting 7500 gallons and released 950 gallons.  Failure on the tank was on the head of the tanker on left hand corner.  The damage was about a 3 foot tear.  Spill supplies were immediately placed.  An environmental cleanup contractor was on site to begin response within 2 hours.

column168: Driver was traveling on State Road 821 (FL Turnpike) at mile marker 23 in the center lane. Driver could not  avoid debris on the roadway from prior accident. After striking the debris the vehicle overturned resulting in a spill of approximately 6,100 gallons of gasoline. Shield Engineering managed the cleanup.   Shield dispatched Cliff-Berry, Inc. (CBI) to aid with recovery and cleanup. CBI noted a sheen on the  SW 60th St canal. Booms were placed in the roadside ditch and the outfall into the canal. CBI recovered  as much product as possible from the stormwater drains, concrete areas, and from the roadside ditch  itself.   Due to the quantity of gasoline released, as well as the impact to surface waters and the shutdown of  the highway, Shield notified the National Response Center (NRC) of the release within the first few hours  of the incident occurring (Incident Report #1312240). Shield also completed a Discharge Report Form  for the Florida Department of Environmental Protection, and provided a summary of the release and initial  response to the Miami-Dade County Department of Regulatory and Economic Resources.
column169: This accident was non-preventable for our driver. There was a large piece of debris in the roadway that could not be avoided. It appears that a truck in the prior accident had a generator fall from his truck and that was what our driver could not avoid.

SequenceEvent: The package was discovered on van line 3, by the HD side of the belt on a pallet. The driver had noticed that the Fiberboard box looked damp and had some discoloration so he brought this to QA's attention for inspection. QA placed this package in a bin and brought it over to the HazMat cage for further inspection. DescribePack: Upon inspection, there are 2 bottles of Reagent Alcohol that spilled due to loose caps and insufficient inner packing material. The spill however did not come out of the box due to the thickness of the fiberboard and the alcohol substance drying off quickly. Spill was kept within the box only. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Package was placed inside of a red HazMat bin and placed in a separate Pallet in the HazMat cage for Flammable Liquids. The spill was kept within the box and did not spill out due to the fiberboard box material and the alcohol product drying quickly within the box.

SequenceEvent: Package was at the end of the IC Belt and was pushed of the end by other packages down the line causing it to drop top down. SequenceEvent: At some point during transit this package was upside down causing a loose cap on 1 bottle of cleaner. upon discovery the bottom of the package was wet but there was no spillage outside of the box. Used rubber gloves and placed hazmat inside Hazmat drum. DescribePack: loose cap on 1 bottle caused by package being placed upside down at some point. The bottle was in a plastic bag so when the box was placed upright the leakage flowed to the bottom of the plastic bag that was now torn. this caused the bottom of the outer box to become wet. though 1/5th of the contents are missing from the bottle no leakage was found outside of the box. It appears the damage happened someplace else and was ignored. DurationRel: 8 and MitigateEffect: package was placed in hazmat drum as there was no leakage found outside of the package.

column168: SequenceEvent: Package was found with gray stains in corners.  Content was inspected for damage.  Content included 6 one quart metal cans. DescribePack: Upon inspection, 3 cans showed dry drip streaks down the side. DurationRel: 0 and MitigateEffect: When found by QA, package was already in a red hazmat carrying tote.

SequenceEvent: Package handlers were unloading a trailer from Nashville Hub and noticed a leaking package. The package handlers notified management who then notified Quality Assurance personnel. The spill inside of the trailer was approximately 1 gallon. The package handlers immediately left the area and the spill was cleaned up properly with Hazardous Materials PPE. No one was harmed. The remaining gallons and package that contained the plastic gallon sized bottles were brought to the Hazmat area of the building. DescribePack: The package was very flimsy and seemed almost re-used. Inside the package the four 1 Gal. plastic bottles were loosley placed without any type of inner packing material to prevent the bottles from movement. The caps/lids of the plastic gallons were not secure. The small piece of tap on top of them did not stick well. There was too much space inside of the package. The bottle either hit the side of the box or one of the other gallons. As a result, the cap loosened on one of the four gallons and the corrosive machine detergent spilled out inside and ultimately - outside of the package. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: The spill release was cleaned up immediately after discovery. Package handlers left the area until the scene was safe. The contents were placed inside of a hazmat bin and transported to the hazmat area where the damage was inspected thoroughly.

column168: Transwood Carriers experienced the reported release of approximately 315 gallons of a UN1203 Gasoline resulting from a dropping of the tanker / failure of the landing gear. The release reportedly impacted the asphalt roadway and adjacent soil shoulder & ditchline. No storm drains or waterways were reported to have been impacted. Local first responders secured the release with sand. An environmental contractor was dispatched to perform the remedial and restorative site operations. All waste was collected, containerized and taken off site for disposal.   Initially, a tire on the Transwood Carriers tractor locked up and caught fire. The driver was disconnecting the tractor from the tanker when the landing gear failed resulting in the release of the UN1203 Gasoline. The tanker / release was not impacted by the tractor fire.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: Logiflex notified ERTS of a spill in Talent, OR. It was reported that approximately 2 gallons of UN1791 "Hypochlorite Solution" were released from a 55-gallon poly drum due to improper loading. At the time of the release impact was only to the trailer floor. No storm drains or waterways were impacted. ERTS dispatched an environmental contractor to investigate, secure and remediate the release. Patriot Environmental personnel have located the leaking drum. They confirmed that it was not damaged. The drum had a loose bung cap that allowed approximately 3-4 gallons of material to release onto the trailer floor when the drum fell over. They are re-securing the drum and it's bung cap. The remaining pallets will be offloaded from the trailer in order for them to clean the trailer floor. Patriot personnel have completed the cleanup and resecured the trailer. The leaking drum was uprighted and the leaking bung cap was resecured, it will be shipped on with the rest of the drums. Patriot personnel are leaving the site with the 55-gallon poly drum of waste.

column168: On 7/2/2021 at around 10:00 AM, Kansas City Southern Railway(KCS) Transportation personnel reported loaded tank car SHPX 207610 (SULFURIC ACID, SPENT, UN1832, Haz Class 8, PG Il) Ieaklng from the top of the car at the KCS rail yard In Port Arthur, TX. The KCS Environmental& Hazmat Department mobllized railroad qualified response contractors to secure the car and monitor air quality. Upon arrival, responders Identified the source of the release, and were able to stop the leak by tightening the cap on the liquid line one quarter turn. Estimated release was 3 gallons. The remaining closures, fittlngs and valves were checked for securement and the outside of the car decontaminated. The product on the ground was neutralized and properly disposed. After verifying the car was secure, SHPX 207610 was released back into transportation. File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated based on the best information available at the tlme offiling. This shipment was offered as a'bulk' shipment, aka one car load, therefore the exact amount offered in this package is not known to the carrier. This carrier does not have access to mass balance data which can exactly quantify this value.

column168: On 07/07/2021 at approximately 1315, dangerous goods Administration received a call from Employee# 414657 at the heavyweight facility in Ontario, Canada. reporting an undeclared resin solution shipment. The reporting agent noticed that the shipment was labeled with a ground limited quantity mark. He contacted the shipper to identify the· contents in the package to which the shipper replied that they contents were merely car parts and gave the agent verbal permission to remove the ground marking. The agent then noticed the product labeling on the side of the box which indicated that the package contained red dielectric coating. Under managerial instruction, the agent opened the package to confirm that the contents matched the label and noticed that the lid on the inner aluminum container appeared to have vented, resulting in some of the red coating spilling. A corresponding safety data sheet was found online that verified that the coating identified as resin solution. The shipment is being held pending an FAA investigation.

column168: APPROXIMATELY 2 TO 3 GALLONS OF WASTE MATERIAL LEAKED AT THE TAPLIN YARD ON 7.21.21. THE DRIVER BROUGHT THE PRELOADED TRAILER TO THE TAPLIN YARD. DRIVER DID NOT NOTICE ANY SPILLAGE ON THE HIGHWAY AS HE WAS DRIVING. DRIVER NOTICED SPILLAGE AT THE TAPLIN YARD WHEN HE MADE THE TURN AT THE TAPLIN'S FUEL ISLAND. TRUCK AND TRAILER WERE PARKED ON THE CONTAINMENT PAD IN THE YARD AND LEAKAGE STOPPED. DRIVER MADE CALLS FOR ASSISTANCE FOR HELP CLEANING UP THE SPILLED MATERIAL IN YARD. SAFETY CAME OUT TO HELP THE DRIVER PUT OIL DRY DOWN. ADDITIONAL PERSONNEL SHOWED UP TO HELP SWEEP AND CLEANUP OIL DRY.   TRAILER WAS INSPECTED BY THE TRANSPORTATION MANAGER (TM) AND THREE WING NUTS / DOG EARS, WERE LOOSE ON THE DOME/MANHOLE AT THE TOP OF TRAILER. THE TM TIGHTENED THE DOG EARS BY HAND AND WRENCH. TRAILER WAS BACKED UP AND PULLED FORWARD AND THE TOP MANHOLE STILL LEAKED SLIGHTLY. SPILL PADS HAD BEEN PLACED AROUND THE DOME WHEN TESTING TO CATCH ANY POTENTIAL LEAKAGE. TRAILER WAS SECURED AND DOME WAS OPENED BY SAFETY AND FOUND 1/3 OF THE DOME GASKET WAS NOT SEATED CORRECTLY IN THE DOME. GASKET WAS REPLACED, DOME WAS CLOSED AND TIGHTENED. TRAILER WAS AGAIN MOVED TO TEST FOR LEAKAGE AND NO LEAKAGE OCCURRED. SPILL RESIDUALS WERE CONTAINERIZED FOR PROPER DISPOSAL TRAILER WENT ON TRIP FOR DISPOSAL 7.22.21. NO ISSUES TO REPORT WITH TRAILER. THIS ENTIRE SCENARIO TOOK APPROXIMATELY 1 HOUR.
column169: THIS TANKER IS ON A DEDICATED RUN HAULING WASTE SOLVENT. THE PROCEDURE GOES AS FOLLOWS. TANKER IS LOADED BY GENERATOR SITE PERSONNEL. LOAD IS BOTTOM FED AND VAPORS FROM VENTING ARE CAPTURED. THE TOP MANHOLE IS NOT ACCESSED DURING LOADING. TRANSPORTER IS HANDS OFF DURING THE LOADING PROCESS. THE TANKER AND LOAD IS THEN STAGED ON A CONTAINMENT PAD AT THE TRANSPORTERS SECURE FACILITY, FOR TRANSPORTATION THE NEXT DAY. LOAD IS DELIVERED TO THE DISPOSAL SITE. DISPOSAL SITE PERSONNEL OBTAIN A SAMPLE VIA THE TOP MANHOLE FOR TESTING. UPON VERIFICATION / APPROVAL THE LOAD IS OFF-LOADED AT THE DISPOSAL SITE.  DISPOSAL SITE PERSONNEL NEED TO VERIFY THE FOLLOWING;  THE DOME GASKET IS PROPERLY SEATED. ALL OF THE DOG EARS ARE PROPERLY TIGHTENED.  THE TOP MANHOLE IS SECURELY CLOSED AFTER SAMPLING.

column168: Approximately 2 to 3 gallons of waste material leaked at the Taplin yard on 7.21.21. The driver brought the preload trailer to the Taplin yard. Driver did not notice any spillage on the highway as he was driving. Driver noticed spillage at the Taplin yard when he made the turn at the Taplin's fuel island. Truck and trailer were parked on the containment pad in the yard and leakage stopped. Driver made calls for assistance for help cleaning up the spilled material in yard. Safety came out to help the driver put oil dry down. Additional personnel showed up to help sweep and cleanup oil dry.  Trailer was inspected by the Transportation Manager (TM) and three wing nuts / dog ears, were loose on the dome/manhole at the top of trailer. The TM tightened the dog ears by hand and wrench. Trailer was backed up and pulled forward and the top manhole still leaked slightly. Spill pads had been placed around the dome when testing to catch any potential leakage. Trailer was secured and dome was opened by Safety and found 1/3 of the dome gasket was not seated correctly in the dome. Gasket was replaced, dome was closed and tightened. Trailer was again moved to test for leakage and no leakage occurred. Spill residual were containerized for proper disposal.  Trailer went on trip for disposal 7.22.21. No issues to report with trailer. This entire scenario took approximately 1 hour.
column169: This tanker is on a dedicated run hauling waste solvent. The procedure goes as follows. Tanker is loaded by generator site personnel. Load is bottom fed and vapors from venting are captured. The top manhole is not accessed during loading. Transporter is hands off during the loading process. The tanker and load is the n staged on a containment pad at the transporters secure facility, for transportation the next day. Load is delivered to the disposal site. Disposal site personnel obtain a sample via the top manhole for testing. Upon verification / approval the load is off-loaded at the disposal site.  Disposal site personnel need to verify the following;  The dome gasket is properly seated. All of the dog ears are properly tightened. The top manhole is securely closed after sampling.
